\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 1993, they expand their old paper by adding bond assets and other factors
 to explain bond returns such as 
\emph on
term structure
\emph default
.
 In addition, instead of Fama-Macbeth approach, this paper uses Black, Jensen,
 Scholes (1972) time-series regression approach.
 Monthly stock and bond returns are regressed on the returns to a market
 portfolio of stocks and mimicking portfolio for size, B/M, and term structure
 risk factors in returns.
 The slopes are 
\emph on
factor loading or risk-factor sensitivities
\emph default
 for stocks and bonds.
 This method, later, will be the standard in testing factor models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model, the dependent variable is excess returns (stock and bond returns
 minus one-month Treasury bill rate).
 Bonds include 2 government bonds and 5 corporate bond portfolios.
 Stocks include 25 of 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 size-BM portfolios.
 The idea is if the intercept from three-factor regressions (excess market
 return, mimicking size, and mimicking B/M factors) are close to zero, the
 model seems to do good job to explaining the cross-section of average stock
 returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Multifactor explanations of asset pricing anomalies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main finding of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fama1996multifactor"

\end_inset

 is they propose 3-factor model (
\begin_inset Formula $FF3$
\end_inset

) to solve most of anomalies 
\emph on
except for momentum
\emph default
.
 The existing anomalies are: long-term reversal (DeBondt and Thaler, 1985),
 short-term momentum (Jegadeesh and Titman, 1993), size, B/M (Lakonishok,
 Shleifer, and Vishny, 1994), which cannot be explained by CAPM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Form factors:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At the end of June in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, independently sort median ME of NYSE stocks and 3 groups of BE/ME (30-40-30%)
 of NYSE stocks.
 We got 6 portfolios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Value-weighted monthly returns on portfolios are calculated from July year
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to June year 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two factors: 
\begin_inset Formula $SMB=\frac{SL+SM+SH}{3}-\frac{BL+BM+BH}{3}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $HML=\frac{SH+BH}{2}-\frac{SL+BL}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Three-factor models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{i}-R_{f}=a_{i}+b_{i}(R_{m}-R_{f})+s_{i}SMB+h_{i}HML+e
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the three factors can proxy for all risk exposure to unobservable factors,
 we should see the intercepts are close to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fama and French often analyze by using two methods:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two-way sort
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Run factor model regression of 10 deciles (sort based on the anomalies)
 then test GRS that all intercepts are zero.
 If we accept the null, meaning that FF3 could explain the anomaly because
 all intercepts are zero.
 For example, if they test B/M, they first sort sample to 10 deciles of
 B/M then run factor models for 10 portfolios.
 Then, they test all 10 intercepts are zero by GRS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
A 5-factor model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fama2015afivefactor"

\end_inset

 update their model to include two more factors: investment and profitability.
 They propose a theoretical base that market value equity to book value
 equity of firms is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{M_{t}}{B_{t}}=\frac{\sum_{\tau=1}^{\infty}E(Y_{t+\tau}-dB_{t+\tau})/(1+r)^{\tau}}{B_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where Y is earning, B is book equity, 
\begin_inset Formula $dB_{t+\tau}=B_{t+\tau}-B_{t+\tau-1}$
\end_inset

 is change in book equity, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is long-term average expected stock return.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Implications of the model is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
M decreases and B/M increases: so stock returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 increase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E(Y_{t+\tau})$
\end_inset

 increases (i.e., 
\series bold
profitability factor
\series default
) then stock returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 increase
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $dB$
\end_inset

 increases (i.e., 
\series bold
investment factor
\series default
) then stock returns 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 decreases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical model is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{i}-R_{f}=a_{i}+b_{i}(R_{m}-R_{f})+s_{i}SMB+h_{i}HML+r_{i}RMW+c_{i}CMA+e
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the new two factors are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
RMW (robust minus weak profitability, as ROE)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
