\begin_layout Subsection
Innovations of variables relating to 
\emph on
investment opportunity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is known that to some extent, 
\begin_inset Formula $SMB$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $HML$
\end_inset

 could explain some variation in cross-section returns.
 But Fama and French could not explain what are these factors proxy for.
 Specifically, FF (1993) suggest that HML and SMB might proxy for state
 variables that describe 
\emph on
time variation in the investment opportunity set
\emph default
.
 Fama and French (1996) argue that the SMB and HML factors of the Fama and
 French (1993) model proxy for financial distress.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Petkova (2006-JF) propose an idea that these factors are correlated with
 
\series bold
\emph on
innovations 
\series default
(i.e., changes)
\emph default
 in variables that describe investment opportunities.
 In other words, the FF model is consistent with an ICAPM explanation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In literature, some empirical findings show that FF factors relate to macroecono
mic variables and business cycle fluctuations (FF factors predict future
 GDP growth or consumption growth).
 In this paper, Petkova uses a set of relevant state variables such as 
\series bold
\emph on
short-term T-bill, term spread, aggregate dividend yield, and default spread
\series default
\emph default
.
 These state variables are chosen to model 
\emph on
two aspects
\emph default
 of the investment opportunity set, namely, 
\series bold
\emph on
the yield curve
\series default
\emph default
 and the 
\series bold
\emph on
conditional distribution of asset returns
\series default
\emph default
.
 In this paper, she does not assume that HML and SMB have predictive abilities
 for the excess market return.
 Rather, they proxy for innovations (i.e., changes) in variables that possess
 such ability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A factor model with excess market return and innovations in the aggregate
 dividend yield, term spread, default spread, and one-month T-bill yield
 has a higher explanatory power than the FF three-factor model.
 FF factors are not significant explanatory variables for the cross-section
 of average returns in the presence of these innovation factors.
 Furthermore, this suggestive ICAPM model could be able to account for common
 timevarying patterns in returns (conditional asset pricing model).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
What is ICAPM framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to 
\series bold
(Merton, 1973)
\series default
, if investment opportunities change over time, then assets’ exposures to
 these changes are important determinants of average returns in addition
 to the market beta.
 So, Petkova looks at the innovations in state variables that capture uncertaint
y about investment opportunities in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{it}=a_{i}+\beta_{iM}R_{Mt}+\sum(\beta_{i,u^{K}})u_{t}^{K}+e_{it}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 is returns on 25 portfolios sorted by 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 size and B/M, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{M}$
\end_inset

 is excess market return, 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{K}$
\end_inset

 is the innovation to state variable K.
 The innovation is the unexpected component of the variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For state variables, she adopts a VAR model that demeanded vector 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}$
\end_inset

 follows a first-order VAR as 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{t}=Az_{t-1}+u_{t}$
\end_inset

, where the residual 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the innovation terms and is also the risk factor in the model above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More details about state variables: choose a set of state variables to model
 two aspects of the investment opportunity set, these are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To capture 
\emph on
yield curve slope
\emph default
: short-term T-bill yield (RF) and the term spread (TERM) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To capture 
\emph on
conditional distribution of asset returns
\emph default
: aggregate dividend yield (DIV), the default spread (DEF), and interest
 rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
She also adds SMB and HML of Fama-French as a comparison.
 Thus, the FF3 model is also adopted as a competing asset pricing model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Default risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vassalou and Xing (2004) use Merton (1974) option pricing model to calculate
 default measure of individual firms.
 They find that size effect is a 
\emph on
default effect
\emph default
, and this is also largely true for the book-to-market (BM) effect.
 The size effect 
\emph on
exists only
\emph default
 within the quintile with the 
\emph on
highest default risk
\emph default
, which the spread between small and big firms is 45%/year.
 In the highest default risk quintile, the B/M spread is 30%/year.
 In low default risk segments, the size effect and B/M effects disappear.
 Small and value stocks have higher default risk than big and growth stocks
 and the relation is monotonic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, they find that high default-risk firms earn higher returns
 than low default-risk firms, only for small and high BM firms.
 It is clear that the highest returns are earned by stocks that are either
 both small in size and high default risk (DLI), or both high DLI and high
 BM.
 Finally, they find that default risk is systematic and therefore priced
 in the cross section of equity returns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Fama–French (FF) factors SMB and HML 
\emph on
contain some default-related information
\emph default
, but this is 
\emph on
not the main reason
\emph default
 that the FF model can explain the cross section of equity returns.
 SMB and HML appear to 
\emph on
contain important priced information
\emph default
, unrelated to default risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While in literature, default risk on equities focus on default spread (long-term
 BAA corporate bonds minus long-term AAA or US Treasury bonds) from bond
 market, they estimate the 
\emph on
default likelihood indicators (DLI) 
\emph default
from equity data.
 In Merton model, equity of a firm is viewed as a call option on firm asset.
 Because equity holders are residual claimants on the firm’s assets after
 all other obligations have been met.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{A}$
\end_inset

 is assets value, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is book value of debt, market value of equity is the call option of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{A}$
\end_inset

 with time to expiration equal to T.
 Apply the Black and Scholes (193) model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{E}=V_{A}N(d_{1})-Xe^{-rT}N(d_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where r is risk-free rate, N is cdf of the standard normal distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The default probability is the probability that the firm assets will be
 less than the book value of firm liabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{def}=Pr\left(V_{A}\leq X|V_{A}\right)=Pr(ln(V_{A})\leq ln(X_{t})|V_{A})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And distance to default: 
\begin_inset Formula $DD=\frac{ln(V_{A}/X)+\left(\mu-\frac{1}{2}\sigma_{A}^{2}\right)T}{\sigma_{A}\sqrt{T}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Default occurs when the 
\emph on
ratio of the value of assets to debt is less than 1
\emph default
, or its log is negative.
 The DD tells us by 
\emph on
how many standard deviations
\emph default
 the log of this ratio needs to 
\emph on
deviate from its mean
\emph default
 in order for default to occur.
 
